{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_bubley_ver02/data/sn82016181/0052904009A/1945110201/0088.xml":{"full_text":"THE WASHINGTON DAILY NEWS. FRIDAY. NOVEMBER IMS\n40\nEight Million Jobless by April\nIs a Pessimistic Prediction\nBy PETEK EDSON\nTop Government economists are now pretty well out on a limb with predictions of 8,000,000\nunemployed by next April.\nThis is the pessimistic side of the picture. It is based on the belief that everything is going to\npot, following the pattern of the post-war depression of 1922. It takes discouragement from the\nbelief that employers are holding back on opening up new jobs until Government wage and price\npolicies are settled, that strikes will increase, that wage cuts will reduce purchasing power, and\nthat everyone will hang onto his savings for food and shelter instead of spending them for new\nautos, ice boxes and such things, to create a post-war boom.\nThe other side of the picture is more*\noptimistic. It is based on the belief\nthat what lies ahead is merely a little\nreadjustment recession, following the\npattern of 1919. It takes encourage\nment from the belief that as soon as\nbusiness gets squared away and begins\noperating under lower taxes in 1946.\nj^liere will be a big pick-up and things\nwill begin to get good. Under this line\nof thinking, there won\u2019t be any eight\nmillion unemployed next spring.\nLESS THAN EXPECTED\nIn support of this latter view, it must\nbe admitted that from the V-days up\nto Nov. 1. the shock of unemployment\nhas been a darn sight less than most\nof the prophets of doom have been\nwailing. This can be seen best in\nreports on state unemployment com\npensation figures. It is impossible to\nchart these figures and project them\nto show what the situation will be\ncome spring. But the figures do show\nthat any idea U. S. war workers are\nnot now finding or not taking peace\ntime jobs is completely cockeyed.\nIt is pretty well established that end\nof the war and cancellation of war\ncontracts threw over six million work\ners out of jobs.\n650.009 FILE CLAIMS\nIn the first 10 days after VJ-Day.\n650 000 laid-off war plant workers filed\nclaims for job insurance. The last\nweek in August it was 496.000. First\nweek in September it was 296.000. First\nweek in October it was a little above\n200 000. and first week in November it\nwill probably be under 200.000.\nIt is not safe to say this marks the\ndownturn in the tide of reconversion\nu employment, says Clague. The trend\nmay be reversed in coming weeks. But\nas of mid-October, when there were\nonly 1.750.000 ex-war workers regis\ntered for unemployment insurance. 10\nper cent, or between 175,000 and 200,000.\nwere being dropped off the rolls be\ncause they had found new jobs. In\nother words, they were dropping off\nthe unemployment compensation rolls\nalmost as fast as they were being\nadded.\nIf this reasoning is correct, it seems\nthat the whole problem ahead depends\non what happens to the returning vet\nerans. To date, 2.225,000 service men\nand women have been demobilized.\nDemobilization is now only one-third\ncomplete, with four million more vets\nplus two million Government workers\nto go by mid-summer. It is normal\nto expect that when a veteran comes\nback he may bump a civilian out of a\njob. That factor could conceivably\nincrease the load on civilian unemploy\nment compensation.\niRRmSTRORG\ngo^TIRES\nFamous for more than 32\nyears for long wearing,\ncool running, safe riding.\nThe standard ot duality since 1812.\nWhen you are entitled to new tires,\nsee us tor Armstrongs\nMAINE'S GAS STATION\n8.W3 Ga. Ave N W\nLAKEMAN'S GAS STATION\nMS R I. Ave N E\nMILES' GAS STATION\n?lth ARI. Ave. N. E.\nWhether the eight million unem\nployed is an April fool prediction de\npends finally on how fast industry can\nopen up new jobs in building, the auto\nindustry, agriculture, the service trades\nand so on\u2014all of which now show a\npotential of employing four or five\nmillion more workers.\nThe street cors you will view ot Copitol Transit's\nCavalcade of Progress are products of St. Louis\nCar Company's quality shops.\nAlso, the quiet and efficient P. C. C. cars on\nWashington's streets\u2014quicker on the start and\nstop than the costliest automobile\u2014are creations\nof this company's engineering.\nFor more than half a century, since the days of\nwooden coaches on steom railroads and of horse\nSt. Laxiis far Company\nSt. Lmi is, Mo.\nEXECUTIVE OFFICES\nSt. Louis\nWE BUY\nDIAMONDS\nOld Gold\u2014Jewelrv\nARTHUR MARKEL\n940 F ST. N.W.\nSt La\\i is Car Cam pany\nTHE BIRTHPLACE OF THE P. C. C. CAR\n\nSee transit history\nbeing made!\nNew York Office\n512 Fifth Ave.\nThe products of this company's 60-acre St. Louis plant include:\nP. C. C. Street Cars\nTrolley Coaches\nDiesel Electric Power Generating Cars\nInterurban Cars\nElevated Cars\nSubway Cars\nFrench, Danes Know\nAtom \u2018Secret\u2019\u2014Urey\nBy United Press\nCHICAGO, Nov. 2\u2014The \u201csecret\u201d of the atomic bomb already\nis out and two European nations beyond the Anglo-Amer\u00df an\ncombine are in possession of its production know-how, a topflight\nU. S. scientist has disclosed.\nHarold C. Urey, Nobel Prize winner, said last night that France\nand Denmark share with the United States, England and Canada\nextensive knowledge of the bomb\u2019s development and production\nUrey, whose research played a vitals 1\nrole in atomic development, told the\nUniversity of Chicago citizens\u2019 board\nthat Niels Bohr, a Dane, \u201cknows more\nabout the atom bomb than I do.\u201d\nHe also named French Scientist\nPierre Auger, who with Bohrs partici\npated in critical research studies at the\nUniversity. Both men, Urey said, were\ngiven a picture of the project denied\ncors on street railways, St. Louis Car Company\nhas pioneered in building ever finer and finer\nvehicles. Today on practically every railroad and\ntransit line, this company is serving America, en\nabling you to travel always with greater speed,\nsafety and comfort.\nThe Transit Cavalcade of Progress is well worth\na visit. Be sure to go. Remember the time ond\nplace: Saturday and Sunday, F Street between\n14th ond 15th.\nWashington Office\nTower Bldg.\nSon Francisco Office\nMonodnock Bldg.\nStreamlined Trains\nPassenger Cars\nBaggage and Mail Express Cars\nChair Cars\nDining Cars\nFreight Cars\nCaboose Cars\nAmerican scientists, whose work\ndepartmentalized.\nThe scientist charged that seeieev\nsurrounding atomic research was a de\nterrent to scientific progress and warned\ni that further control would force the\ni withdrawal of top scientists to work in\n[other fields.\nCleveland Office\n606 Williamson Bldg","height":"14367","width":"10800"}}
